SUMMARY:An Olio House Party: DJ & Curated Conversations
DESCRIPTION:What to expect:8pm: You're matched with new friends to discuss 
 a couple of curated prompts.9:30pm-midnight: DJ Zimmy Dynamite begins and 
 we dance our asses off until he winds down the evening with an ambient set
 . Then\, we'll stretch and have tea because we love our bodies.Tickets:To 
 attend this party you can buy a ticket or sign up for our monthly membersh
 ip which gives you 2 free events each month.You must be 21 or older to att
 end.What is Think Olio?Think Olio is an ongoing experiment in lifelong lea
 rning. We are a community of open-minded people who gather to exchange ide
 as with new friends and connect over art\, literature\, and philosophy.An 
 Olio is what we call the social learning events we’ve been organizing si
 nce 2015. A blend between a lecture and a house party\, Olios are led by a
  teacher who loves sharing their passions and the room is filled with curi
 ous\, open-minded New Yorkers.&nbsp\;Eight months into creating a venue\, 
 one of our favorite feelings has been the moments where we’ve stepped ou
 tside of time. We’ve created a space where conversations don’t feel ru
 shed\, people are greeted with hugs\, and as a community\, we spontaneousl
 y come up with new ideas (like the dial-up-disco house party) and bring th
 em to life.Our goal is to spark new perspectives\, ignite curiosity\, and 
 enjoy ourselves socially—an alternative to typical nightlife options.Che
 ck out our full calendarDisclaimer: By purchasing a ticket\, you agree to 
 have your photo/video used for social media/marketing materials. If you pr
 efer to not have your photo taken\, feel free to send us a note.\n\nTicket
 s & info: https://www.viewcy.com/event/olio_house_party
URL:https://www.viewcy.com/event/olio_house_party
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:d612cac7-9e7e-4f7b-bae4-b88e6039ccf8@viewcy.olio
DTSTAMP:20260714T141549Z
DTSTART:20260913T190000Z
DTEND:20260913T213000Z
SUMMARY:The Stories We Inherit: A Four-Week Family Mapping Workshop
DESCRIPTION:The Stories We Inherit: A Four-Week Family Mapping WorkshopMost
  of us have a sense that our family history matters. That the people who c
 ame before us\, and the dynamics between them\, live on in us in ways we f
 eel but can’t always understand. But few of us have had the chance to lo
 ok at the nuances of our ancestors' lives and their dynamics closely\, or 
 to approach our family members with genuine curiosity and ask the question
 s we've never thought to ask\, or were afraid to. Alongside family systems
  theory\, emerging research in fields like epigenetics has fueled curiosit
 y about the many ways the experiences of previous generations may continue
  to shape our lives today.Over four weeks\, we'll come together as a group
  and each build a genogram (visual map of our family) in order to deepen o
 ur understanding of where we come from and the patterns that have shaped u
 s. The genogram is grounded in family systems theory: the idea that a fami
 ly isn't a collection of separate individuals\, but an interconnected emot
 ional unit\, with a rich tapestry of emotional patterns.&nbsp\;Unlike a fa
 mily tree\, a genogram doesn't just track bloodlines. It captures the emot
 ional patterns between family members\, the texture of their relationships
 \, the influence of key events\, and the cultural and systemic forces that
  have shaped the family over time. As a group\, we’ll learn to read it\,
  and prepare for real conversations with family members in-between session
 s.We'll meet as a small group of no more than 15\, guided by Monica Setaru
 ddin and Kate Hakala — two MFT students who bring their personal practic
 e and clinical training to this work. As part of their training\, they con
 structed genograms and bore witness to each other’s stories. They discov
 ered how historical exploration can lead to personal transformation\, unlo
 cked curiosity\, and entirely new conversations with their oldest connecti
 ons. This is a tool typically used by MFT therapists and clients to facili
 tate relational healing. Seeing the impact it's had on us and the people i
 n our lives not just as clinicians but as humans\, we're eager to bring it
  outside the therapy room and into your hands.&nbsp\;This is a shared jour
 ney of guided self-discovery: a space to learn together through instructiv
 e sessions\, engage in self-inquiry\, and be in conversation with a small 
 community doing this work alongside you. While this is not therapy\, the f
 acilitators will approach your story with the positive regard\, reverence\
 , and openness it deserves.SessionsFour sessions\, 2.5 hours each\, Sunday
 s 3–5:30pm\, beginning September 13. A one-week break falls between sess
 ions 3 and 4 to give participants time to conduct their family interviews 
 before the group reconvenes.Over four weeks\, you will:Build a personal ge
 nogram spanning three generations of your familyLearn key concepts from fa
 mily systems theory in plain\, non-clinical languageIdentify recurring the
 mes and patterns running through your familyPrepare for and conduct real i
 nterviews with family member(s)Connect your family story to your present-d
 ay relationships with yourself and othersWitness and be witnessed in a sma
 ll\, trust-based communityWhat You'll ReceiveGuided teaching and discussio
 n: Weekly instruction grounded in family systems theory and relational the
 rapy\, made accessible in a non-clinical setting.Family map support: Guida
 nce in building your own genogram across three generations\, with facilita
 tor support along the way.Small-group learning community: A cohort of no m
 ore than 15 people\, building relationships and engaging in cross-dialogue
  over four weeks.Family interview preparation: Tools for initiating and co
 nducting conversations with family members — how to prepare\, how to han
 dle what surfaces\, and how to make meaning from what you hear.One-on-one 
 mentorship: Each participant receives a private conversation with the faci
 litators to discuss their family map\, themes\, and questions.Weekly take-
 home exercises: Reflection prompts and exercises to build your family map\
 , prepare for interviews\, and deepen personal inquiry between sessions.Ab
 out the TeachersThis series is facilitated by Monica Setaruddin and Kate H
 akala\, Marriage and Family Therapists in training and rising second-year 
 students in Iona University's MFT program.Monica SetaruddinMonica is deepl
 y passionate about family and relational therapy — particularly generati
 onal patterns\, cultural heritage\, and family lineage as pathways to self
 -awareness and insight into how we relate to ourselves and others. Her app
 roach weaves together training in family therapy\, years of personal work 
 in therapy\, Internal Family Systems\, and somatic and contemplative pract
 ices\, and twelve years working in global public health understanding how 
 systemic power and structural inequity shape families and communities.Kate
  HakalaKate was drawn to the field of relational therapy\, guided by a bel
 ief that healing happens within context. Her own generational experiences 
 of family blending and non-traditional caregiving have widened her definit
 ion of family and fostered her interest in group dynamics. For 15 years\, 
 she's worked as a writer and editor\, with a focus on connections\, cultur
 e\, and the issues facing modern relationships. By connecting individuals 
 to authenticity\, accountability\, and self-compassion\, she is invested i
 n helping others reauthor their lives.Who This Is ForThis series is open t
 o anyone curious about better understanding their families and the pattern
 s running through them. No background in therapy or family systems require
 d. You don't need to have a "difficult" family story — just a genuine in
 terest in understanding your own. This is best for people who have the tim
 e and capacity to engage between sessions. There will be homework: buildin
 g your family map\, reflecting on what you find\, and reaching out to fami
 ly members for conversations. The work that happens outside the room will 
 help guide our sessions each week.&nbsp\;At least one interview with a fam
 ily member is required for participation.ScholarshipsWe have a small numbe
 r of scholarship spots available for those facing financial barriers. If c
 ost is preventing you from participating\, please reach out with a short n
 ote about why this series would be meaningful for you. Scholarships are of
 fered on a rolling\, first-come basis.We especially welcome BIPOC individu
 als and children of immigrants\, recognizing that spaces centering these f
 amily experiences and histories can be rare.\n\nTickets & info: https://ww
 w.viewcy.com/event/the_stories_we_inheri
URL:https://www.viewcy.com/event/the_stories_we_inheri
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:14d0485a-b231-43c2-8400-7e21cc67ef00@viewcy.olio
DTSTAMP:20260714T141549Z
DTSTART:20260914T230000Z
DTEND:20260915T010000Z
SUMMARY:Calling Up the Inner Chorus: A Four-Night Workshop on Our Inner Cri
 tics\, Allies\, and Creative Callings
DESCRIPTION:Do you sense that something creative is trying to emerge in you
 r life? Perhaps there's a project you've been imagining\, a practice you'd
  like to begin\, a change you're considering\, or simply a desire to bring
  more creative purpose and expression into your life? Are you an artist al
 ready pursuing a creative career\, but feel passive or reactive\, and long
  to direct your creative life more powerfully?Wherever you are in your cre
 ative journey\, for many people — and especially for artists — the mom
 ent they begin to clarify a creative aspiration or imagine a different fut
 ure for themselves\, another voice quickly takes center stage: the inner c
 ritic.Perhaps you've heard this voice too:"I'm too lazy." "I'm not talente
 d enough." "I'm too old to start." "I'll never\, I can't\, I won't..."When
  these critical voices arise (which is a completely normal part of the cre
 ative process)\, our instinct is often to fight them\, silence them\, or s
 urrender to them altogether. A quick survey of popular self-help and inner
  critic workshops suggests that this is the standard response: tame the in
 ner critic\, overcome the inner critic\, banish it\, erase it.In this four
 -session Olio\, we'll take a different approach.Drawing from Jungian psych
 ology\, folklore and mythology\, coaching\, and creativity studies\, we'll
  get curious about the critical voices that accompany creative life. Rathe
 r than trying to conquer these parts\, we'll explore how we might understa
 nd\, engage with\, and in some cases\, collaborate with them.As we do so\,
  we may even discover that the very capacities we cultivate as artists and
  creative people are the very tools we need to respond to and work creativ
 ely with these voices\, even uncovering new creative possibilities along t
 he way.We'll also broaden our perspective beyond the inner critic to explo
 re the larger chorus of voices within us — some quieter\, yet supportive
  and wise. How might we recognize and enlist these inner allies as we purs
 ue creative work\, set meaningful goals\, and build a rich and fulfilling 
 creative life?Through playful exploration — not therapy\, and not self-i
 mprovement so much as a kind of creative detective work — we'll investig
 ate this inner chorus and develop a more dynamic relationship with our inn
 er world. Participants will leave with greater clarity\, renewed creative 
 momentum\, and practical tools for moving more confidently toward a creati
 ve calling.Sessions Four sessions\, Mondays 7:00–9:00pm\, beginning Sept
 ember 14 at the Olio Lighthouse.Session One: The Mythology of the Inner De
 mon Learn the origins and archetypal dimensions of the inner critic throug
 h mythology\, folklore\, and Jungian psychology\, and begin to explore the
  personal mythologies\, creative belief systems\, and stories we carry.Ses
 sion Two: Collaborating with Your Inner Critics Discover tools and approac
 hes for understanding\, engaging\, and working constructively with critica
 l inner voices.Session Three: Discovering Inner Allies (and Other Voices) 
 Identify supportive inner figures\, values\, and perspectives that can hel
 p guide creative work and decision-making.Session Four: Creative Visioning
  Bring these insights together to clarify a direction and envision the nex
 t chapter of your creative life.What to ExpectA grounded introduction to J
 ungian archetypes and shadow workFrameworks drawn from folklore\, mytholog
 y\, creativity studies\, and coachingGuided exercises and creative practic
 es designed to make the work personal and accessibleAn approach to visioni
 ng and goal-setting that recognizes how identity\, social location\, life 
 circumstances\, and larger cultural contexts shape what feels/is possible 
 and meaningful for each of usA playful\, exploratory atmosphereOpportuniti
 es for reflection and conversation within a small groupOur Teacher: Justin
 e Williams (she/they) Described as "wickedly funny" (SF Gate)\, Justine Wi
 lliams is an artist\, performer\, filmmaker\, and educator whose work cent
 ers play\, collaboration\, and social imagination. Since 2013\, Justine ha
 s been on faculty at the Yale School of Drama\, where they teach acting th
 rough play and guide interdisciplinary collaboration.A celebrated teacher\
 , Justine has led workshops internationally and runs The Play Society\, a 
 roving school and creative lab dedicated to training and new work developm
 ent through an ethos of play and collaboration. They hold an MFA in Perfor
 mance and Interactive Media Arts from CUNY/Brooklyn College.Justine's coll
 aborations include a decade-long creative partnership with Eva Peskin expl
 oring queer friendship and world-building\, and an ongoing project with ar
 tist and death doula Kate Muehlmann that invites public engagement with qu
 estions of death and dying.Their work has been presented and supported by 
 The Public Theater\, Ars Nova\, The Metropolitan Museum of Art\, Abrons Ar
 ts Center\, Dixon Place\, New Georges\, Queer|Art\, The Orchard Project\, 
 and more.\n\nTickets & info: https://www.viewcy.com/event/calling_up_the_i
 nner
