SUMMARY:Freud\, Jung & Fairy Tales: Different Cultures same Subconscious 
DESCRIPTION:Big bad wolf. Evil stepmother. Poisoned apple. Doors that shoul
 d not be opened. These enchanting archetypes inhabit the world of fairy ta
 les and appear in our nightmares\, superstitions\, and doodles. Freud and 
 Jung viewed these persistent archetypes as products of universal anxieties
  and desires\, making fairy tales a precious window into the human psyche.
  A close re-reading of them allows for a minimally invasive procedure to i
 nvestigate — and potentially heal — our traumas.In this four-part Olio
 \, Dina Odnopozova (PhD Yale\, professor at Baruch) draws on Freud and Jun
 g to explore why humans have been telling the same stories and dreaming th
 e same dreams for centuries. Each class focuses on a single archetypal plo
 t in its European and non-European variations.SessionsFour sessions\, Tues
 days 7pm-9pm\, starting October 6\, 13\, 20\, 27 at the Olio Lighthouse.Cl
 ass One: Don't Wear Red! — Little Red Riding HoodA coming-of-age tale ab
 out innocence\, stranger-danger and victim-blaming.Class Two: Don't Eat Ra
 ndom Apples! — Snow WhiteA dark tale of envy\, aging\, beauty obsession 
 and necrophilia. &nbsp\;Class Three: Don't Trust Your Parents! — Hansel 
 and GretelA fairy tale that taps into our fundamental fear: being abandone
 d by the people meant to protect us.Class Four: Don't Ignore Red Flags! 
 — BluebeardInspired by a notorious wife-killer\, this chilling tale asks
  an enduring question: is blissful ignorance better than painful truth?\n\
 nTickets & info: https://www.viewcy.com/event/freud_jung__fairy_t
